DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(93)90127-Q
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030440769390127Q
AB  - Two Bayesian and one non-Bayesian test statistics are derived to test the hypothesis that stochastic regressors in a truncated structural equation are independent of the error term. The truncation is caused by an indicator function. Sampling experiments are conducted to examine sizes and powers of the test statistics and to compare them with those of the Mroz test. The tests are also applied to a labor supply equation for married women to see whether the wage variable is exogenous. The Michigan Panel Study of Income Dynamics data for 1976 are used.
